26,212 through August 9th. The big wildcard here is what happens when the moratorium ends (either by court order or non-renewal). Either way, the numbers should stay under 1,000 per week through September. Then, either the numbers will return to an average year (landing us in bin 2) or we see a spike in evictions (likely putting us in bin 3). I don't see much of a chance that the moratorium lasts through the end of the year (needed to get bin 1). I also can't image a huge flood of backlogged evictions bringing us into a normal year (bin 4). It seems even less likely that such a backlog floods the system with an entire year's worth of paperwork during the last quarter (bin 5).

Today, the Supreme Court blocked part of New York's eviction moratorium. The order applies to a provision that bars evictions of tenants who file a form declaring economic hardship, rather than provide evidence in court (NYT). "It's not clear how many people could be immediately affected. More than 830,000 households in New York State, the majority of them in NYC, are behind on rent, with a total estimated debt of more than $3.2 billion" The report in the NYT quotes a state senator who says it appears landlords could start filing suits immediately to evict tenants. But a patchwork of other state and federal protections remains in place that could stop their suits from succeeding, including the CDC eviction moratorium which includes all of NYC. About $100 million, or less than 4% of the state's $2.7 billion total has been spent from federal relief dollars given to NYS.(NYT) The money is there, it's a matter of the state and city getting it together to process applications. I know they are offering grants to non profits to start processing applicants but those are themselves scrambling to get staffing and trained them.
The CDC extension to Oct really cuts the chances of the higher bins. I'm heavily weighting the second bin due to the chance that the moratorium really does end at some point.

The 2020 number is a poor base rate, given the moratorium during most of the year. The average from the data file for prior years is 223k, or about 19k per month. So, a simple exercise of YTD (23,596) plus the average for the remaining five months gets you to 116,590. This seems like the most appropriate starting place. However, a look at the data for 2020 before COVID (through March 15) reveals that near term numbers were already 30% below average. This leads me to wonder if the base rate values are inflated.

There were 35.8k evictions in 2020 before the eviction moratorium (about 416/day), and about 38.5k evictions between the start of the moratorium and the end of the year (about 137/day). Based on the 2021 filings up to and including the week of June 20th, there have been about 113/day. Assuming all of the evictions that didn't happen between March 27, 2020 and now ended up in a backlog, there are currently about 130k pending evictions.

The new extension was granted in part as owners say federal funds to help people pay back rent is available but it is not being disbursed quickly enough. The city needs to help expedite the application process and ease requirements in terms of documentation (other state-funded programs for rent relief last year were said to only have approved 15% of applications, they had to reopen the application period a few months later and review all applications that had been denied. State reps and community orgs said the application was requiring too many documents that were difficult for people to get in the middle of the pandemic).
Based on my observation, we will have at least 2x the current eviction filings from 2020.
